This week, International Olympic Committee Commissioner Duecker Pound caused an international uproar by saying that "if the epidemic does not end in May, the Tokyo Olympics will be cancelled" .

While the Japanese government and the International Olympic Committee said preparations for the Games in Tokyo continued as planned, the WHO said it was not in a position to make a decision on cancelling the games in the short term. But financial markets have begun to consider the potential risks, affected by a surge in confirmed cases in several countries around the world in recent days.

The first is the one billion that the insurance industry will have to pay.

Although normally insurance designed for cancellations does not include compensation for cancellations of Infectious Diseases (such as the Mobile World Congress in Barcelona earlier this year) , Allianz product experts say, organizers of major international events usually attach provisions relating to infectious diseases.

Allianz clarified last week that although it had agreed to underwrite 2028, it had no exposure to the Tokyo Olympics. The director of Munich Re, also based in Germany, said on Friday that the company had provided "hundreds of millions of euros" in cancellation products for the Tokyo Olympics.

The real problem is that, in addition to International Olympic Committee, event organizers, sponsors, and even local hotels and car rental companies buy similar insurance. Factoring in television broadcasters and sponsors, Jefferies estimates that the Games are insured at an estimated $2 billion, while the olympics-related hospitality industry has about $600 million covered.
